  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contract obligations to New Mexico total $13.1B in FY2026 to date, with 6,862 awards and an average award size of $1.9M. Obligations are down 2.9% year over year. The Department of Energy accounts for the largest share of buying activity at $9.8B, and Facilities Support Services is the largest industry sector at $9.7B. The vendor landscape is concentrated: TRIAD NATIONAL SECURITY, LLC has $5.1B in obligations and NATIONAL TECHNOLOGY & ENGINEERING SOLUTIONS OF SANDIA, LLC has $4.5B. Construction-related sectors such as Commercial and Institutional Building Construction and Water and Sewer Line and Related Structures Construction together represent sizable commitments of $1.8B and $223M, respectively. Fiscal-year comparisons show gradual growth through FY25, with obligations by fiscal year recorded as $11.6B in FY21, $11.7B in FY22, $12.4B in FY23, $13.1B in FY24, $13.5B in FY25, and $13.1B in FY26 to date. Current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date).",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "What agencies account for most federal spending in New Mexico?",
        "body": "The Department of Energy is the dominant buyer at $9.8B in FY2026 to date. The Department of Homeland Security follows with $1.9B, and the Department of Defense is third at $741M. Other agencies with notable obligations include the Department of the Interior at $298M and the Department of Health and Human Services at $137M."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which vendors and industries capture the largest obligations?",
        "body": "TRIAD NATIONAL SECURITY, LLC leads vendors with $5.1B, followed by NATIONAL TECHNOLOGY & ENGINEERING SOLUTIONS OF SANDIA, LLC at $4.5B and FISHER SAND & GRAVEL CO at $1.8B. Facilities Support Services is the top industry at $9.7B; Commercial and Institutional Building Construction is next at $1.8B. Other industry commitments include Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences (except Nanotechnology and Biotechnology) at $223M and Water and Sewer Line and Related Structures Construction at $223M."
      }
